### Keyframe operation family placement in the existing op-family/CompositionGraph architecture (complete)

`keyframe.add`, `keyframe.update`, and `keyframe.remove` are net-new operations with no existing home. Research where they belong: as new entries in TimelinePatchOpFamily, as graph-owned operations under the reserved `graph.edge.*` wildcard, or as a separate keyframe-operation system.

- `keyframe.add`, `keyframe.update`, `keyframe.remove` have zero occurrences anywhere in the codebase — confirmed net-new with no existing home.
- The `TimelinePatchOpFamily` union defines 13 active families (clip.*, track.*, asset.*, app.update, project-data.*, extension.noop) — all operate on top-level timeline-config entities (clips, tracks, assets, app data). Keyframe ops would be the first family targeting nested data (automation keyframes inside clip params).
- The `TimelinePatchReservedOpFamily` union includes `graph.node.*`, `graph.edge.*`, `graph.group.*`, `clip.split`, `clip.slice` — all marked 'validated but not executed in M3'. The compiler explicitly skips reserved ops: it issues a warning diagnostic (`timeline-patch/reserved-op`), skips payload validation, skips execution during compilation (line 991-992), and sets `fullyPreviewable: false` in preview results. Reserved ops produce zero diff entries.
- Placing keyframe ops under the reserved `graph.edge.*` wildcard would make them non-executable — they'd validate as warnings and silently skip compilation, contradicting the M3b requirement for executable keyframe patch semantics to be implemented before M4.
- A parallel graph-owned operation path already exists in nascent form: `patchPreview.ts` defines `GraphPreviewOperation` as `GraphShaderAssignOp | GraphShaderRemoveOp`, with `applyGraphPreviewOperations()` applying them to a cloned `CompositionGraphInput` and returning `CompositionGraphPreviewResult`. This pattern bypasses `TimelinePatch` entirely.
- The `CompositionGraph.preview()` signature (line 244 of graph.ts) is a zero-argument closure `() => CompositionGraphPreviewResult | undefined` — it captures operations via closure (`createGraphPreviewWithOps`) rather than accepting them as arguments. This means keyframe ops on this path would also need to be closure-captured.
- The bridge from TimelinePatch to graph operations exists via `extractGraphPreviewOps()` (line 1889) which maps `clip.update`/`app.update` patch operations to internal `GraphShaderAssignOp`/`GraphShaderRemoveOp`. No equivalent bridge exists for keyframe ops.
- Keyframe data models live in two places: (a) `src/sdk/video/families/automation.ts` defines `Keyframe`, `KeyframeInterpolation`, `AutomationClipTarget`, `AutomationClipParams` as public SDK contracts for baked keyframe curves on automation clips — these are data-only types with no operation family concept; (b) `src/tools/video-editor/keyframes/index.ts` provides host-owned deterministic interpolation/validation/recording utilities — also with no operation family concept.
- Keyframe operations semantically differ from existing families: they mutate nested data (the `keyframes` array inside `AutomationClipParams` on an automation clip) rather than top-level config entities. The existing compile path operates on `TimelineData` working copies (clips, tracks, meta, clipOrder) — keyframe ops would need to reach into clip params, which is a different mutation target.
- The `graphProjector.ts` already projects automation-annotated clips into `animates` graph edges (lines 316-367), reading `automation.keyframeCount` from clip summaries. This means keyframe additions/removals should update graph edges, suggesting graph-owned operations may be the natural authority path.
- No existing code maps `graph.edge.*` to any executable behavior — it is purely a pass-through placeholder. Tests confirm it produces zero diff entries in all compilation scenarios (timeline-patch.test.ts lines 290-322).
- Three distinct integration points exist: (1) `TimelinePatchOpFamily` via the `validateTimelinePatch`/`compileTimelinePatch` pipeline; (2) reserved `graph.edge.*`/`graph.node.*` as a placeholder wildcard (currently no-op); (3) `GraphPreviewOperation` via `applyGraphPreviewOperations` → `projectCompositionGraph` as a separate graph-owned path.

